<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Personal experience with Wis and Int.<br>
Created 3 characters First two High Elf, 3rd one Gnome. All 3 Enchanters with 0 skill in Blacksmithing: <br>
1) Int 120 Wis 107<br>
2) Int 107 Wis 120<br>
30 Int 133 Wis  67<br>
After 100 attempts each making metal bits;<br>
characters 1 and 2 both reached skill cap of 21 (for metal bits) around 90. Both had created exactly 60 successful metal bits. <br>
Character 3 was skill level 17 after 100 attempts. Reached 21 on 123 attempt. Also 60 successful metal bits created.<br>
Personal belief (and granted I may be very wrong in this) is that skill rate increase is based on combination of wisdom and intelligence scores. In this case the one with the highest int actually had the slowest increase. The other 2, although having their scores reversed were still equal combined, learned at the same rate. <br>
Wisdom had no affect on success rate. Success rate was based entirely on skill level. Success rate for making metal bits in all 3 cases began around 20% at 0 level and increased to 80% after reaching skill cap of 21. Success rate continued to increase to 95% as Blacksmithing skill increased. At the same skill level the success rate was the same whether the character had 67 WIs, 107 Wis or 120 Wis. <br>
Anyway these were just my findings from one experiment. Others may have different results. Would like to hear what luck others have had and what their Wis/Int ratio was.<br>
Brewbane from Prexus</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
